Consider the substitution postulate as it relates to equality:
â–º A quantity may be substituted for its equal in any statement of equality.

A quantity may be substituted for its equal in any statement of inequality.

The Trichotomy Postulate
We know that if x represents the coordinate of a point on the number line, then
x can be a point to the left of 3 when x < 3, x can be the point whose coordinate
is 3 if x = 3, or x can be a point to the right of 3 if x > 3. We can state this as a
postulate that we call the trichotomy postulate, meaning that it is divided into
three cases.
Given any two quantities, a and b, one and only one of the following is true:
a <b
a = b or a> b.
